I am extremely proud to host Roque Pech, a Dreamer, a DACA beneficiary, a local teacher and member of the Wilmington Neighborhood Council, as my guest to tonight’s Joint Session of Congress.     I invited Roque because I believe it is important to show Trump the face of one of thousands of DACA recipients that continue to make our country better.    As a DACA recipient who has been spared from deportation, Roque is just one good example of the continuing contributions immigrants provide to our country.     I will continue to stand up for the people like Roque, who are American in every way.

Today I stood outside DOJ to tell Jeff Sessions to resign immediately.    It is well known that Sessions was a long-serving Donald Trump campaign advisor, not just a “surrogate from time to time” as he testified.  The fact that he spoke with Russia’s ambassador to the United States last year, which is contrary to testimony he provided under oath to the Senate Judiciary Committee during his confirmation hearings, is a slap in the face to our American values.  I reiterate my call for an independent, bipartisan, transparent commission to investigate this Administration’s connections and communications with Russia.

For Immediate Release March 28, 2017     Rep. Barragán: Trump Guts Climate Policies to Fund Corporate Polluters   Washington, DC –  Congresswoman Nanette Diaz Barragán (D-CA), Member of the Natural Resources Committee and Chair of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Task Force on Clean Energy, Environment, Public Lands, and Water issued the following statement on President Trump’s Executive Orders on climate and the environment today.  “President Trump’s executive order guts our climate policies and clean energy jobs in order to boost the profits of corporate polluters.  In my district, there are kids who walk around with asthma inhalers around their neck.  These actions are an attack on the very air we breathe, the water we drink, and the land on which we stand.  My constituents and I care about a safe, clean and healthy environment and we will not let the Trump Administration get away with destroying it.”

March 30, 2017 Statement for the Congressional Record   U.S. Representative Nanette Diaz Barragán – Trump Dirty Energy Executive Order   After the hottest recorded year in history, Donald Trump and his Environmental Destruction Agency under Administrator Scott Pruitt will undo more than a decade’s worth of progress fighting climate change and protecting public health by seeking to eliminate the Clean Power Plan as we know it. The Clean Power Plan which seeks to reduce carbon pollution from fossil-fueled power plants by more than 30 percent, was the biggest action the United States had ever taken to reduce carbon pollution, the main source driving climate change. It was also the lynchpin of the Paris Climate Agreement which brought countries from all over the world together for the first time to combat climate change.  By weakening the Clean Power Plan and retreating as the world’s leader in combating climate change, the Trump Administration is giving away the ever-growing clean energy economy to China. Contrary to President Trump’s assertions, these actions will not bring back coal-mining jobs in Appalachia as natural gas continues to be more economically competitive than coal, the main reason for coal’s demise. The climate gap, the sometimes hidden and often-unequal impact of climate change on people of color and the poor, is real and only getting worse. Climate change disproportionately impacts minority and low-income communities like those in my district, especially with respect to heat waves, air quality and extreme weather events. Low-income and minority communities in the inner city are more susceptible to the “heat island” effect where temperatures are magnified by concrete and asphalt.  Reports have shown that African Americans living in Los Angeles are twice as likely to die as other Angelenos during a heat wave. One of my top priorities is the issue of environmental justice - people should not breathe dirtier air simply because of their income or what they look like. As a United States Congresswoman for California’s 44th congressional district, I will do everything I can to ensure clean air, water and lands for vulnerable populations.

Media Advisory:  TODAY: Homeland Members to Tour Port of Los Angeles and Port of Long Beach, Discuss Impacts of Port of Entries, Trade, and Inspection ________________________________________ LONG BEACH, CA – Rep. Nanette Diaz Barragán, whose district includes the Port of Los Angeles, will host her colleagues from the House Homeland Security Committee to tour the nation’s largest Port Complex comprised of the Port of Los Angeles and Port of Long Beach, receive briefings from the U.S. Department of Homeland Security, including the U.S. Coast Guard and U.S. Customs and Border Protection, and discuss inspection methods, trade zones, and the impact of port of entries.  Following the briefings, members will host a media availability to discuss the impact of operations and the region.  WHO:  Congressional Members • Ranking Member Bennie G. Thompson (D-MS) • Rep. Filemon Vela (D-TX) • Rep Nanette Diaz Barragán (D-CA)  • Rep. Luis Correa (D-CA)   WHAT: Media Availability   WHEN: Monday, April 17, 2017, 2:30 PM (PDT)   WHERE:   The Port of Los Angeles Downtown Harbor (Mini Pier) 504 South Harbor Blvd., San Pedro, CA  90731 Adjacent to The Maritime Museum 600 Sampson Way, San Pedro, CA  90731   To attend, please RSVP to Jazmin Vargas at jazmin.vargas@mail.house.gov

If we needed another reason as to why we should study history, here it is.  The firing of Comey, on top of other officials who were investigating the wrongdoings of the Trump Administration, looks like President Nixon’s "Saturday Night Massacre."  It is simply stunning and troubling that when an employee does not agree with the President, they are suddenly fired.    This abrupt action only raises more red flags into the actions of the administration and leads to further speculation of a cover up.  This does not seem to be a coincidence.  As I have done for months, I continue the call for the Department of Justice to appoint a special counsel – someone as far away from the White House as possible – to properly investigate the probe into the 2016 election and any other connection these Trump officials have to Russia.  Additionally, I echo the call for Congress to hold immediate emergency hearings to obtain testimony directly from Attorney General Sessions, the deputy attorney general, and FBI Director Comey.

I want to let you know about an important vote today that could erode the rights of patients and consumers to seek justice.   Today the house will debate and vote on H.R. 1215, the Protecting Access to Care Act. This bill will destroy patients’ ability to recover damages and upend the med mal system as we know it. If passed, this bill would lead to increased healthcare costs, more injuries and deaths, and limit non-economic damages to $250,000. It also would apply to nursing home claims and reduce pharmaceutical industry liability. In short, it's dangerous.   I will be on the debate floor today to argue against the bill then I will vote against it.  I stand with the trial lawyers to oppose this harmful bill.  As an attorney, I understand the importance of defending access to our courts and justice for all.

I’m committed to serving the veterans who live in my community and across the nation. Today I introduced a bill that will get more vets get off the streets. Nobody who fought for this country should be without a home. We don’t leave our vets behind, and definitely not without a roof. The bill is the Housing Homeless Veterans Act of 2017. It prioritizes the allocation of rental assistance vouchers under the HUD-Veterans Affairs Supportive Housing (HUD-VASH) program to areas of the country that have the largest populations of homeless vets with the greatest need for rental assistance, places like Los Angeles County and #CA44. Read more here: https://barragan.house.gov/media/press-releases/barrag-n-introduces-bill-get-homeless-vets-streets

Today I introduced legislation that will make it easier for military families to send care packages to a loved one deployed in a combat zone. The Military Care Package Program Act of 2017 will waive Postal Service mailing costs whenever a family member sends a package to their combat-deployed father or mother, husband or wife, brother or sister, or child. Having watched my sister put together care packages for her husband serving in Afghanistan and Iraq, I know military families shouldn't be worried about mailing costs when they send a care package, Care packages are far more than snacks or books. They’re vital reminders of the family that service members left behind to serve our country.

Joined Mayor Eric Garcetti, Councilmember Joe Buscaino, and representatives from our armed forces to welcome Fleet Week to the Port of Los Angeles in the City of Angeles.

Faces of DACA: Fernando Navarrete is a Dreamer. He’s lived in the United States since he was 6. He graduated from Cal State Dominguez Hills, landed a job at a start-up and mentored high school students. He later became a community organizer. “I decided to take the leap into public service,” he said. These days he works for L.A. Councilman Joe Buscaino. The United States is his only home. “I don’t know anything outside of the U.S.” People like him are why we #DefendDACA.
Excited to join Mayor Eric Garcetti, Councilmember Joe Buscaino, and members of the Armed Forces as we kick-off Fleet Week at the Port of Los Angeles!

Alein is a Dreamer. She’s lived in the United States since she was 9. She’s mid-way through a public health grad degree at UCLA, and the first in her family to graduate from college. “My parents made a lot of sacrifices for myself, my brothers,” she said. If DACA is canceled “my education would be impacted. I won’t be able to get a job. I wouldn’t be able to drive.” People like Alein are why we #DefendDACA.

Faces of DACA: Roque Pech is a Dreamer. He’s lived in the United States since he was he was 3. He’s is a teacher. He spent two years teaching math in public schools. He coached middle school football. Today he works at a non-profit teaching other teachers how to integrate technology into the classroom. DACA “was like something was lifted from my shoulders,” he said. “Living in the United States undocumented can feel dehumanizing, I would never wish that feeling on anybody." People like Roque are why we #DefendDACA

Faces of DACA: Mecir is a Dreamer. He’s lived in the United States since he was 12. He works for a non-profit helping abused and mentally ill children. “I don’t call anywhere else home. I just love L.A., and I love Southern California—and I love the U.S.,” he said. “I call myself American. I feel American. My dream is to become an American citizen.” People like Mecir are why we #DefendDACA.

I’m a great believer in education. It’s the great equalizer, it’s what will prepare #CA44 for 21st century jobs. Congress should do everything we can do make college more affordable. But the #GOPtaxbill being rushed through the House would make education even more expensive by eliminating the student loan deduction. I’m sticking up for our district: I’ll vote against this plan to put #BillionairesFirst.

Education is the number one equalizer.  As a kid, my parents, immigrants from Mexico, told me I had to go to college to have a better life. Congress should be working on debt-free college. Instead the House GOP is considering a bill that will make it harder to afford college. Today I went to the House floor to urge a vote against the #GOPtaxbill. Millennials and young workers, if you disagree with the plan, make your voice heard.

The GOP tax bill will devastate anyone with a chronic disease. It eliminates the itemized medical deduction, which lowers the taxes of people who pay a lot for medical care. Today on the House floor, I said I can’t sit idly by while my Republican colleagues put forth a tax bill that takes money from the sickest and neediest among us in order to give tax cuts to corporations and the top 1 percent of earners.

A GOP colleague on the House Natural Resources Committee tried telling me that science doesn’t show that living close to oil wells results in a public health crisis. In #CA44, we know the truth only too well. We breathe in the pollution of oil wells operating in our backyards. We see the children with asthma, the people with lung diseases. I will not stand for this. Although my amendment to require new oil wells be set back at least 1,500 feet from houses, school and businesses didn’t get passed by the committee today, I’ll continue to fight for it. See my response in the video below.

Happy Thanksgiving!  Today is a day to show gratitude for the blessings in our lives, spend time with the people we love, and share all that is good in our lives with those less fortunate.  Today also marks my last day on a tour to thank the men and women who serve in our Armed Forces overseas — from Poland to Qatar and Afghanistan. As we helicopter from one location to another in Afghanistan today to visit our service members and thank them for their sacrifice and service, let me take a moment to thank you. I truly value your friendship and support.  I have so much to be thankful for today — family, friends, a job I love and for living in the greatest country on Earth.   I am also grateful for service members like Army Gen. Lathrop from the California National Guard who sacrifices time away from loved ones while risking his life to uphold our ideals and freedoms. I met Gen. Lathrop in Afghanistan while serving and eating Thanksgiving dinner with our service members. He is from our district and has family that currently lives in San Pedro. One of the highest honors I have as a Member of Congress is being able to nominate exceptional young men and women who reside in California’s 44th Congressional District to serve in our nation’s academies – The U.S. Military Academy (West Point), the U.S. Naval Academy, the U.S. Air Force Academy and the U.S. Merchant Marine Academy.   To start your request for a Military Academy Nomination from my office, please complete the online form at https://barragan.house.gov/services/military-academy-nominations. A member from my staff will then contact you to request the following supplemental materials: • 3 letters of recommendation (at least 2 academic) • High school transcript/college transcript • American College Testing Program (ACT) results and/or College Board Scholastic Assessment Test (SAT) results. • Resume of extracurricular activities • An essay stating why you want to attend a service academy (1-2 pages) • Current photo   For more information please contact my office at 310-831-1799.   The deadline to submit an application is this Friday, December 1, 2017 at 5 PM.

If you or someone you know is interested in applying to one of our nation’s Military Service Academies, the deadline to apply for a nomination from my office is this Friday, December 1st at 5PM. Please visit my website by clicking below or call my office at 310-831-1799 for more information!   https://barragan.house.gov/services/military-academy-nominations

Diabetes is one of the leading causes of disability and death in the United States. It can cause blindness, nerve damage, kidney disease, and other health problems if it’s not controlled. Everyday our friends, family, and neighbors suffer disproportionately from diabetes. CA-44 has the highest percentage of diabetic individuals in California. Together, we must prevent, treat and beat diabetes.   This National Diabetes Month, remember to seek help on how to manage your diabetes or help raise awareness about diabetes risk factors and encourage people to make healthy changes. To learn more please visit https://www.nih.gov/.

REMINDER – Tomorrow is the last day to apply for a Military Academy Nomination from my office. Please visit https://barragan.house.gov/services/military-academy-nominations of call us at 310-831-1799 for more information.

Rep. Nanette Diaz Barragán to Promote Urban Greenspaces   SAN PEDRO, Calif.—On Monday July 10, at 10 a.m., Congresswoman Nanette Diaz Barragán (D-San Pedro) will outline her new bill to promote funding for urban parks. The Congresswoman will discuss some of the potential projects that will be eligible for funding.  The most livable cities are dotted by greenspaces. That’s why Rep. Barragán has introduced legislation in Congress to create a dedicated source of funding for urban projects that expand outdoor recreational opportunities, particularly in underserved areas.   The Outdoor Recreation Legacy Partnership Program Act of 2017 (H.R. 2943) would codify a federal grants program that offers matching funds to state and local governments investing in much-needed outdoor outlets for city residents. It has bipartisan support.  Who: Rep. Nanette Diaz Barragán (D-San Pedro) joined by Port of Los Angeles Deputy Executive Director of Development Tony Gioiello and representatives from the Urban and Community Park Coalition  What: Announcing the Outdoor Recreation Legacy Partnership Program Act of 2017 (H.R. 2943)  When: Monday, July 10, 2017, 10:00 a.m.  Where: Green Grass area at the end of Nagoya Way (South of 1200 Nagoya Way, San Pedro CA 90731)
